"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function returns an array of sinc values, but the sinc function is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) if x != 0, and sinc(0) = 1. When x is an integer, the sinc function will return 1 for x = 0 and 0 for other integer values of x. However, the sinc function is not guaranteed to return exactly 0 or 1 due to floating point precision issues. Therefore, comparing sinc_result[0] and sinc_result[1] to 1 and 0 respectively using the '==' operator may not work as expected.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7c7\\n<assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n---\\n>assert np.isclose(sinc_result[0], 1), \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n8c8\\n<assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n>assert np.isclose(sinc_result[1], 0), \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\"\n}"